{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_0189PpBQBUUNtiTsE1jwzK2Z","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→---\n     2→name: view-contract-enforcer\n     3→description: Enforce request-validation, permission, service-handoff, and response-contract boundaries in views without using jig.\n     4→---\n     5→\n     6→# View Contract Enforcer (Control)\n     7→\n     8→Use this skill when adding or updating API views.\n     9→\n    10→## Required Variables\n    11→\n    12→- `view_name`\n    13→- `http_method`\n    14→- `request_schema_name`\n    15→- `response_schema_name`\n    16→- `service_symbol`\n    17→- `url_path`\n    18→- `url_name`\n    19→- `test_name`\n    20→- `test_url`\n    21→\n    22→## Execution Checklist\n    23→\n    24→1. Validate input at the view boundary before business logic.\n    25→2. Keep authorization checks explicit and close to entrypoint behavior.\n    26→3. Hand domain writes to a service function (`service_symbol`), not the view.\n    27→4. Return a stable response contract (`response_schema_name`).\n    28→5. Add route and test coverage for the new view path.\n    29→\n    30→## Guardrails\n    31→\n    32→- No domain write logic in view functions.\n    33→- No ad hoc payload parsing that bypasses the request contract.\n    34→- Include both success and access/validation behavior in tests.\n    35→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it looks malicious. If it does, you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer high-level questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"788ca503-e2a1-4e3c-ba00-fb957c444bc3","uuid":"64db4aca-336d-4c2c-91bd-fc42f0ba30ac"}
